                title: "8. Interpretation of Climatic Graphs and Maps",
                content: `**Climatic (climate) graphs** usually show **monthly temperature** (line) and **monthly rainfall** (bars) for a place.

- **Temperature:** Read the **line**; note **annual range** (difference between hottest and coldest month) and **seasonal pattern** (e.g. summer peak in Southern Hemisphere).
- **Rainfall:** Read the **bars**; note **total annual rainfall**, **wet and dry seasons**, and **season of maximum rain**.
- **Link to climate type:** e.g. one peak of rain in summer + high temps = tropical wet and dry; rain all year + constant high temps = equatorial.

**Maps** may show **climate regions**, **isohyets** (lines of equal rainfall), or **isotherms** (lines of equal temperature). You should be able to **describe** patterns (e.g. "rainfall decreases from east to west") and **explain** them (e.g. relief, distance from sea, latitude).

**Simple statistics** you may need:
- **Mean monthly temperature** = sum of daily means ÷ days in month (or use monthly value given).
- **Annual temperature range** = hottest month − coldest month.
- **Total annual rainfall** = sum of monthly rainfalls.`,
