                title: "4. Landforms Resulting from Weathering",
                content: `Weathering, together with erosion and mass wasting, creates many distinctive landforms, especially in **temperate and tropical** latitudes (including Zimbabwe).

**Inselbergs / Monadnocks** — Isolated rock hills that rise **abruptly** from a gently sloping or flat plain. (Inselberg = German "island mountain"; monadnock = isolated mountain.)
- If dome-shaped and formed from granite-gneiss, they may be called **bornhardts**.
- Common types: **castle kopjes** (piles of boulders), **tors** (exposed jointed rock), **balancing rocks** (e.g. Epworth, Zimbabwe), and **conical hills** with rectangular sides.

**Ruwares / Dwalas / Whalebacks** — Large, smooth, rounded rock outcrops (often granite) left after surrounding material has been weathered and eroded away. Common in Zimbabwe (e.g. Domboshava).

**Karst landscapes** — Formed in **limestone** regions where chemical weathering (carbonation) dissolves the rock. Features include: **limestone pavements**, **sinkholes**, **caves**, **underground rivers**, and **stalactites/stalagmites**.

**Mountain peaks** — When the softer outer material is eroded away, the hard **rock core** of a mountain is exposed, forming sharp peaks.`,
